  "body": " Washer Method: Identify the Error   The region bounded by and for is revolved about the line . A student sets up the following volume integral using the washer method: Which statement best identifies the error in the student's work?      The radii were measured from instead of from the axis .    Correct! Because the axis lies below the region, each radius must be increased by to account for the gap between the axis and the nearest boundary. In general, when the axis is , the radii are and .      The limits of integration should run from to to reflect the position of the axis.    Incorrect. The limits of integration are determined by the x -extent of the region being rotated, which is still . Shifting the axis of rotation never changes the limits; it changes the radius expressions instead.      The outer and inner radii are swapped; it should be and since on .    Incorrect. On we have (check: at , ), so is indeed the outer boundary. The student has the orientation right but is measuring radii from the wrong baseline.      The formula should use instead of because the solid is generated by a full rotation.    Incorrect. The washer-method formula is ; the factor of (not ) already accounts for a full revolution. The factor appears in the shell method, where it represents the circumference of a cylindrical shell.     "
